@swole_dolphin To sum it up. Find where the cable comes into your house.screw your modem cable as close to that as you can. Check the ends for any wire touching the copper. Let me know if that helps. It’s not hard just seems like a lot. Sorry for the long post but wanted to be descriptive.
@swole_dolphin This is what I mean, look at the ends of your cables. If you see any of these silver wires touching that copper try and remove it. https://t.co/W6BKms04B0

@swole_dolphin Also the line going to your modem. Check the ends blow on them and see where the copper wire comes out at the end has and of the silver insulating wire wrapped around it that will also effect speeds. If you see silver wire touching the copper wire end remove it.
@lethalfeather Well they don’t show up not your problem lol
@swole_dolphin Every split drops your signal and interferes more each split.

@swole_dolphin This is what I mean by splitter. Some houses have tons of them and that will destroy your speeds. You see where it says In. You want your internet cable the first one on the left bottom. The in should be the line coming inside from your house. https://t.co/dbY116xs5P

@swole_dolphin 2... make sure the line going to your modem is the closest line to the one coming in from the house. So if you have a bunch of splitters running lines through your house for cable tv make sure the one to your modem is the first one next to the one coming inside your house.

@swole_dolphin 1....It looks like cox is cable internet, first thing to do is make sure you have as few cable lines to your modem as possible no splits. Preferably 1 cable from where your line comes into your house to your modem.
